It is a small reddish lesion, protuberant, fleshy, and well-defined.It is located preferably in the palms of the hands and the soles of the feet [1].A 77-year-old hypertensive woman presented to our consultation for the appearance of a painless nodular lesion on the second left toe, gradually increasing in size for 2 years without any notion of trauma.The pedal pulse was preserved.Histological examination confirmed the diagnosis of eccrine poroma.The patient is still followed at our consultation with no sign of relapse.Atypical localizations such as the scalp and the face can be observed.This tumor can be confused with squamous cell carcinoma or achromic melanoma [5].
